âœª Types of Tunneling Protocols:
1ï¸âƒ£  Generic Routing Encapsulation (GRE) - Simple, point-to-point tunneling protocol often used to create private networks over the internet. ğŸ›¡ï¸
2ï¸âƒ£  Internet Protocol Security (IPsec) - A suite of protocols used to secure internet protocol (IP) communications by authenticating and encrypting each IP packet in a data stream. ğŸ”
3ï¸âƒ£  IP-in-IP - Encapsulates an IP packet within another IP packet, used for forwarding IP datagrams over an IP network. ğŸŒ
4ï¸âƒ£  Secure Shell (SSH) - A cryptographic network protocol for secure data communication, remote command-line login, remote command execution, and other secure network services. ğŸš
5ï¸âƒ£  Point-to-Point Tunneling Protocol (PPTP) - A method for implementing virtual private networks that creates secure point-to-point connections over the internet. ğŸŒ
6ï¸âƒ£  Secure Socket Tunneling Protocol (SSTP) - A VPN protocol that allows VPN client traffic to pass through firewalls securely. ğŸ”¥
7ï¸âƒ£  Layer 2 Tunneling Protocol (L2TP) - A tunneling protocol used to support virtual private networks (VPNs) or as part of the delivery of services by ISPs. ğŸŒ
8ï¸âƒ£  Virtual Extensible Local Area Network (VXLAN) - A network virtualization technology that attempts to address the scalability problems associated with large cloud computing deployments. â˜ï¸
